Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1,50-meter-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was in a dry zone of the Supercontinent Pangea at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window for the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaurs on a day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the trias, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as new species.
During the excavation they carried together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino Early History
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an extraordinary discovery: "Dinosaurier fossils from the trias are extremely rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
The dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago, according to the current teaching opinion.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur-Dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts debated when the exes split into their three main development lines: the carnivorous Theroodes, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged Sauroods known as "long-legged" and their relatives, and the plants eating Ornithicia (birds' saurers), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original Theropode.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, such as the descendants of the Theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight-building buds, probably the common ancestors of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers followed that the waxes appeared there for the first time.
As a result, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America across all parts of the earth, which were still a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangäa.
The fact is that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related Theropods.
