The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the brake distance which a car returns during the braking process.
According to a study by the EU, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving passengers could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would even be fewer accidents - one calculates that every fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects (via radar or camera) obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time it already exerts a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant shall exercise the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
